Is it stable?

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:03.959
What's going on with it?

00:02:03.959 --> 00:02:07.440
So ultimately, we'll answer that question by saying, what is Quarto?

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:12.199
So Quarto is the next generation version of our Markdown for everyone.

00:02:12.199 --> 00:02:15.679
And that everyone kind of has an asterisk to it in terms of not 6 billion people or

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:20.600
whatever is around in the world, but for really any data science language or any future language.

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:25.039
As JJ talked about in his keynote this morning, we want to build a 100-year company.

00:02:25.039 --> 00:02:28.860
And while that today might mean working in R and Python and Julia and JavaScript and

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:33.339
other languages, in the future, we want kind of a language agnostic tool that can work

00:02:33.339 --> 00:02:37.800
with anything, anything that becomes popular in the future.

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:41.600
To make it a bit more clinical instead of just saying the next generation of our Markdown,

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:47.259
Quarto if we define it is an open source scientific and technical publishing system built on Pandoc.

00:02:47.259 --> 00:02:51.020
So Pandoc is a command line tool that's also used by our Markdown.

00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:54.460
So again, there's going to be a lot of familiarity as we go through these slides, and we'll build

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:58.059
up a mental model of how Quarto is a little bit different than our Markdown and some of

00:02:58.059 --> 00:03:00.539
the improvements.

00:03:00.539 --> 00:03:03.740
Quarto itself is a command line interface, or what is called a CLI.

00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:08.740
So you can access Quarto via your terminal, whether in RStudio or any text editor or any

00:03:08.740 --> 00:03:09.740
terminal on your computer.

00:03:09.740 --> 00:03:14.820
In this example, I'm just calling Quarto dash dash help to see what can I do with Quarto

00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:17.500
once I've installed it on my machine.

00:03:17.500 --> 00:03:20.820
It'll print out something like this, and I've abbreviated it so we can see the slides nice

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:25.039
and big, but the commands here that we're looking at are I can use Quarto render to

00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:31.179
render documents from the plain text format out to, say, HTML or PDF or to a website.

00:03:31.179 --> 00:03:35.580
I can use Quarto preview, which will actually render the document and then maintain a background

00:03:35.580 --> 00:03:41.619
web server so as I make changes, it shows those in realtime on the actual rendered output.

00:03:41.619 --> 00:03:45.580
And because it's a publishing system, I can not only render it locally, but I can publish

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:49.580
it to the web, places like GitHub pages or Netlify or something else we'll talk about

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:53.639
in the future called Quarto pubs.

00:03:53.639 --> 00:03:56.940
To really kind of build up our mental model, though, and help differentiate a little bit

00:03:56.940 --> 00:04:01.100
between R Markdown and Quarto, we need to kind of talk about what R Markdown is and

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:03.419
what is happening behind the scenes.

00:04:03.419 --> 00:04:07.100
When you use R Markdown in your daily work, you're probably just thinking, oh, yeah, I

00:04:07.100 --> 00:04:11.380
open up an R Markdown inside our studio, type some code, type some text, and then I

00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:14.419
render it and I get something beautiful out.

00:04:14.419 --> 00:04:17.459
Behind the scenes are things that are happening here in the middle is actually a little bit

00:04:17.459 --> 00:04:18.739
of kind of magic.

00:04:18.739 --> 00:04:19.739
It's not real magic.

00:04:19.739 --> 00:04:20.739
It's code.

00:04:20.739 --> 00:04:23.779
But it's things that are happening as intermediary steps.

00:04:23.779 --> 00:04:28.660
So when you render your R Markdown, the R code is evaluated by a package called Knitter.

00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:33.739
That will evaluate your R code, generate graphics, generate tables, embed HTML widgets and all

00:04:33.739 --> 00:04:35.920
the other magic that you're building.

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:40.320
This generates an intermediary Markdown file or a .md file.

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:45.079
That is then passed to Pandoc, which actually converts a plain text MD into something like

00:04:45.079 --> 00:04:51.200
a report, so a Word document, a PDF report or HTML page, or a presentation, just like

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:55.679
the presentation I'm giving today, something in HTML, or a more complex project like a

00:04:55.679 --> 00:04:58.480
website or a book.

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:01.600
So this process is great and it's been around for almost ten years.

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:05.899
You know, Knitter is an old package, it's robust, we've been using it a long time.

00:05:05.899 --> 00:05:10.100
Something to note, though, is that it has this hard dependency on R. So to use R Markdown,

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:14.420
whether you're using R or other languages, you have to have R, you have to have Knitter,

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:16.140
you have to have R Markdown.

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:20.179
And some of the formatting or preprocessing that occurs to the document actually occurs

00:05:20.179 --> 00:05:24.739
with literal R code written in the R Markdown package.

00:05:24.739 --> 00:05:28.859
For Cordo, we have a similar diagram, and for some of you, if you're not looking closely,

00:05:28.859 --> 00:05:31.579
this might look like the exact same workflow.

00:05:31.579 --> 00:05:33.739
But there's a few differences we'll note.

00:05:33.739 --> 00:05:39.619
For one, rather than using a .RMD, I'm now using a QMD, or a Cordo Markdown document.

00:05:39.619 --> 00:05:43.660
It's going to feel almost identical to R Markdown, which is great.

00:05:43.660 --> 00:05:45.059
And we're still using Knitter.

00:05:45.059 --> 00:05:50.739
So Knitter will evaluate our R code from our QMD, generate an intermediary Markdown file,

00:05:50.739 --> 00:05:53.019
but now we have another word added to Pandoc.

00:05:53.019 --> 00:05:55.299
We have Pandoc with Lua filters.

00:05:55.299 --> 00:06:00.940
So we've moved any preprocessing or postprocessing into Cordo, that command line interface, or

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:05.899
to affect them with Pandoc, rather than having to call them from R.

00:06:05.899 --> 00:06:09.660
What this does is still allows us to create the same reports, presentations, and projects

00:06:09.660 --> 00:06:14.739
that are available, but we don't have to have R in the system to use this.

00:06:14.739 --> 00:06:18.820
You could use Cordo on a fresh computer and not have R anywhere in it, and just render

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:20.980
Markdown as opposed to code.

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:27.420
So people could use it for scientific communication without actually having to execute code.

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:31.500
But because, again, we're trying to become this company that is building for all of data

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:36.619
science and building for scientific communication in general, we want to do more than just evaluate

00:06:36.619 --> 00:06:38.739
for R code.

00:06:38.739 --> 00:06:41.660
So Cordo also extends to other languages.

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:47.260
So Cordo can now use Jupyter and Jupyter kernels as the engine rather than just R and Knitter.

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:51.679
So you can imagine Jupyter kernels include things like Julia or Python.

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:54.380
We also have JavaScript you can execute via Cordo.

00:06:54.380 --> 00:06:58.980
So you have this availability of not just being limited to R, but collaborating with

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:04.019
other people in Python, or if you're a Python dev yourself, also using Python within your

00:07:04.019 --> 00:07:05.660
Cordo documents.

00:07:05.660 --> 00:07:08.540
And again, the output that you're creating is not any different.

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:12.420
You're just using a different engine because you're using a different programming language.

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:14.980
And if I'm using Python, all I have to have is Python on my system.

00:07:14.980 --> 00:07:18.260
If I'm using Julia, all I have to have is Julia on my system.

00:07:18.260 --> 00:07:23.540
And I can switch between them if I wanted to without having to change the overall document.

00:07:23.540 --> 00:07:28.239
For some other people who are working with, say, Julia or Python or familiar with Jupyter,

00:07:28.239 --> 00:07:30.940
they don't want to use a plain text format.

00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:32.579
They might not even use RStudio.

00:07:32.579 --> 00:07:36.380
They want to use Jupyter notebooks or Jupyter lab as their environment.

00:07:36.380 --> 00:07:37.799
And that's possible, too.

00:07:37.799 --> 00:07:42.100
So you can use a literal .ipython notebook or what's called a Jupyter notebook, and whether

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:46.700
using Julia or Python, you can execute code inside of that and with essentially the same

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:49.880
rendering process, create the exact same output.

00:07:49.959 --> 00:07:55.559
So whether using this plain text QMD or a more complex kind of binary format like Jupyter,

00:07:55.559 --> 00:07:59.359
all of those can create the same presentations, the same reports, and the same projects that

00:07:59.359 --> 00:08:02.619
you want to create.

00:08:02.619 --> 00:08:07.200
If we think of what QMD looks like, a little bit to what you're kind of working mental

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:12.399
model of, say, in our markdown document, we have the YAML header or the metadata that

00:08:12.399 --> 00:08:14.600
says do this with my document.

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:18.959
So format HTML, create an HTML static page.

00:08:18.959 --> 00:08:23.320
Here we have side-by-side choice of choosing an engine for Knitter in R or, say, choosing

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:28.679
an engine of Jupyter or a Python 3 or Julia to execute that code.

00:08:28.679 --> 00:08:30.440
And again, you're executing it natively.

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:35.320
You're not wrapping it in R code or wrapping it in Python code to execute the opposites.

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:39.159
You're just evaluating it in its normal engine.

00:08:39.159 --> 00:08:40.239
You can then write some code.

00:08:40.239 --> 00:08:45.200
So we have here a group I summarized with empty cars in dplyr and then in a Python library

00:08:45.359 --> 00:08:49.760
called Suba, both of which look relatively similar, but one's evaluating purely in R

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:52.599
and one purely in Python.

00:08:52.599 --> 00:08:57.719
Then we have a bunch of text or markdown that we're using to create the actual prose or

00:08:57.719 --> 00:09:02.440
the text inside the document, and you can see this spans both columns.

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:06.280
There's no difference in the markdown you're writing or the way that you use Cordo to kind

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:07.960
of typeset your document.

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:11.280
That is the same between any language you're using.

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:15.719
So again, whether you're using R or Python or Jupyter or whatever else, you can write

00:09:15.719 --> 00:09:19.559
these documents and, again, get the exact same output whether you're changing your engine

00:09:19.559 --> 00:09:20.559
or not.

00:09:20.559 --> 00:09:21.559
Cool.

00:09:21.559 --> 00:09:22.559
So we got a plain text format.

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:23.880
It looks kind of similar to our markdown.

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:25.039
I'm still not sold.

00:09:25.039 --> 00:09:26.039
What's the difference?

00:09:26.039 --> 00:09:27.840
So let's talk about that.

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:32.119
Number one, Cordo is one install, what we call batteries included.

00:09:32.119 --> 00:09:35.919
So when you actually install the latest version of RStudio that was released on Monday, Cordo

00:09:35.919 --> 00:09:37.159
is just there.

00:09:37.159 --> 00:09:38.919
It's installed with RStudio.

00:09:38.919 --> 00:09:43.000
So as soon as you download the newest version of RStudio or upgrade it in the future, you

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:44.280
have access to Cordo.

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:45.840
You don't have to install anything else.

00:09:45.840 --> 00:09:47.380
You can just start using it.

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:48.880
You would need an engine.

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:52.640
If you wanted to use R, then you install R. If you want to use Julia, you install Julia.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:54.840
Or Python, you install Python.

00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:58.239
But for at least RStudio users, it's baked into using it.

00:09:58.239 --> 00:09:59.239
So great.

00:09:59.239 --> 00:10:02.640
It's always around and you never really have to think about it or have to update your packages.

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.119
It's just there.

00:10:05.119 --> 00:10:08.559
The other half of that battery is included, though, is that there's a whole bunch of formats

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:12.000
that have been created over the past, you know, five or ten years of R Markdown.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:17.760
So you have your basic formats like HTML documents or Word documents, PDF, different presentations

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:22.400
like this that are made in reveal.js or even advanced layout like distil.

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:24.479
That's several different R Markdown packages.

00:10:24.479 --> 00:10:26.440
In Cordo, it's just all there.

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:30.119
That one install of Cordo brings along all the different formats.

00:10:30.119 --> 00:10:34.039
And it also includes the even more complex formats, so things like websites or blogs

00:10:34.039 --> 00:10:36.520
or books or interactive documents.

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:40.080
All of that can also be done just with the one install of Cordo.

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:42.840
So rather than having to manage a bunch of different R Markdown ecosystems that were

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:47.320
developed at different times and might have different syntax, you have batteries included,

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:50.159
one install with the shared syntax.

00:10:50.159 --> 00:10:54.599
There's still a few things we want to add into Cordo to match full parity with R Markdown.

00:10:54.599 --> 00:10:57.479
Specifically Flex Dashboard is one of the ones that we're really passionate about adding

00:10:57.479 --> 00:10:58.479
quickly.

00:10:58.479 --> 00:11:02.400
And that's a way of creating dashboards with Cordo as well as the older version of Flex

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:04.320
Dashboard in R Markdown.

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:05.320
Great.

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:06.799
So it's a little bit easier to install.

00:11:06.799 --> 00:11:10.039
It might even be installed automatically for you.

00:11:10.039 --> 00:11:12.880
The other part is that you want to stay in the comfort of your own workspace.

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:16.760
If I asked you to, like, bake a cake and I told you to go do it in the corporate kitchen

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:20.320
here, it might be really hard, versus going to your own home and baking it at your own

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:23.359
kitchen table, probably a bit easier.

00:11:23.359 --> 00:11:28.599
Similarly, with Cordo, you get to choose and stay within the comfort of your own workspace.

00:11:28.599 --> 00:11:30.520
So you can obviously use it inside our studio.

00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:32.280
It's preinstalled there.

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:35.000
It's going to, again, feel almost identical to R Markdown.

00:11:35.679 --> 00:11:38.640
So all of that work you've done to learn R Markdown, or if you're learning R Markdown

00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:43.679
or Cordo for the first time, learning Cordo, can be applied within the R Markdown or, sorry,

00:11:43.679 --> 00:11:45.719
within the R Studio ecosystem.

00:11:45.719 --> 00:11:47.200
You still have a button for render.

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:50.840
You don't have to go and use the CLI, but it's still there for you, and it's actually

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:55.559
embedded into different functions that are available through R Studio.

00:11:55.559 --> 00:11:59.239
But again, when you say, oh, I want to collaborate with my colleague or my friend, and they're

00:11:59.239 --> 00:12:03.559
saying, oh, I work in Julia, and I don't really like using R Studio, like, that's not the

00:12:03.559 --> 00:12:08.799
editor I want to use, or I'm a Python dev and I really want to work in a Jupyter notebook.

00:12:08.799 --> 00:12:12.799
Cordo works just as well in a Jupyter notebook, so you can use that as your editor if you

00:12:12.799 --> 00:12:13.799
want to.

00:12:13.799 --> 00:12:17.719
Again, we've got kind of on the left this idea of that's the IPython notebook you're

00:12:17.719 --> 00:12:18.719
working in.

00:12:18.719 --> 00:12:21.719
You're writing pure, normal Jupyter notebook code.

00:12:21.719 --> 00:12:25.159
The only thing that's different is at the top, you now have a raw chunk with the YAML

00:12:25.159 --> 00:12:28.400
that's defining what's the format, what do you want to affect.

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:32.200
And then on the right, you have a Cordo preview, so when you're typing and saving, it'll actually

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:35.960
re-render and show you the output instantly as it builds it out.

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:40.479
And again, maybe you don't like using Jupyter, maybe that's not what you're wanting to look

00:12:40.479 --> 00:12:41.479
at.

00:12:41.479 --> 00:12:44.840
Maybe you use VS Code as your editor and you're really passionate about that because you also

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:48.280
work in, say, JavaScript or other languages.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:52.880
We actually developed a Cordo extension for VS Code, so you get this rich interactive

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:58.280
experience both in like a notebook format, so using, again, a plain QMD as opposed to

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:00.080
a Jupyter notebook.

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:04.479
And you can also do Cordo preview and get that real-time output as well.

00:13:04.479 --> 00:13:08.119
So whatever editor you want or whatever editor you have to collaborate with your colleagues

00:13:08.119 --> 00:13:11.640
on, they can stay in the comfort of their own workspace, you can stay in your own comfortable

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:17.640
workspace and you can still collaborate across a document with a shared syntax.

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:22.000
The other part of what building for RStudio and building for other editors like VS Code

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:26.039
is we have things like rich auto-completion, which wasn't always available and is something

00:13:26.039 --> 00:13:28.039
that's added in Cordo.

00:13:28.039 --> 00:13:32.239
So I'm editing a document, I might remember, oh, yeah, I'm using format HTML, but what

00:13:32.239 --> 00:13:33.239
else can I do here?

00:13:33.239 --> 00:13:38.359
And if I click control space inside RStudio or VS Code, it will pull up all the options

00:13:38.359 --> 00:13:42.760
that are possible, almost like with R code inside the editor, you can hover over it and

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:45.640
see what does this function actually do?

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:48.119
That works in YAML and it also works in chunk options.

00:13:48.119 --> 00:13:52.080
Again, there's dozens of chunk options you can do, and while some of them are very niche,

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:55.739
you're not going to use them all the time, those are very powerful for knowing exactly

00:13:55.739 --> 00:13:59.539
what you need to do and seeing, oh, I need to change figures, I just start typing figures

00:13:59.539 --> 00:14:02.179
and it will auto-complete to what's available.

00:14:02.179 --> 00:14:06.940
And again, whether you're working in Python or R or RStudio or VS Code, this is available

00:14:06.940 --> 00:14:08.419
for you.

00:14:08.419 --> 00:14:09.580
Great.

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:15.419
So we've got some auto-completion in Python and R, maybe we want to talk more about formats

00:14:15.419 --> 00:14:17.020
and we want to get excited about that.

00:14:17.020 --> 00:14:20.299
So this is actually an HTML widget, you'll notice that I'm pulling it over, this is actually

00:14:20.299 --> 00:14:24.539
where we are today, so we're at the national harbor, I can click on this and it says we're

00:14:24.539 --> 00:14:26.260
here together.

00:14:26.260 --> 00:14:29.820
So I can drag that over a little bit, it will load, the Internet's a bit bad in here so

00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:33.340
it's not loaded all the way, but importantly you can see I'm actually interacting with

00:14:33.340 --> 00:14:35.099
it with R code.

00:14:35.099 --> 00:14:38.780
So you can do Shiny, you can do HTML widgets or other things you've built and put those

00:14:38.780 --> 00:14:43.900
into Cordo, and in Python or your Python colleagues, they can also embed what are called Jupyter

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:44.900
widgets.

00:14:44.900 --> 00:14:49.820
So similarly, you have the ability to create interactivity on the client side, both with

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:55.979
Python and with R within a single Cordo document or in separate Cordo documents.

00:14:55.979 --> 00:15:00.619
Another part of interactivity that Cordo adds, though, is beyond just using R and Python,

00:15:00.619 --> 00:15:04.979
it even embeds a version of JavaScript called observable JavaScript.

00:15:04.979 --> 00:15:09.500
This is an extension to vanilla JavaScript created by Mike Bostock who's also the author

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:14.500
of D3, that might be one you're more familiar with in the JavaScript land, and now we have

00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:19.260
a reactive JavaScript library that might look to you like a little bit like Shiny, you know,

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:23.780
I have the ability to create and interact with different tags, and it will actually

00:15:23.780 --> 00:15:28.979
change the graphic, or I can do things like filter the data to have specific build links

00:15:28.979 --> 00:15:33.820
for this penguin's dataset, and again, this is baked into Cordo so you don't have to install

00:15:33.820 --> 00:15:40.340
another thing, this interactivity is added for the document itself.

00:15:40.340 --> 00:15:45.559
So we've got this kind of idea of interactivity, different editors, we can also kind of unify

00:15:45.679 --> 00:15:49.440
a lot of the syntax that was created across years of R Markdown.

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:54.760
So again, this is next-gen R Markdown, it's not being uninstalled from the web and removed

00:15:54.760 --> 00:16:01.159
from the Internet, we're still maintaining it, we'll fix any bugs, but our new dev effort

00:16:01.159 --> 00:16:05.960
is going to go towards Cordo and to Knitter, so Knitter will still power R Markdown, still

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:11.599
power Cordo, but we're focusing on Cordo as this next generation of kind of data science

00:16:11.599 --> 00:16:15.400
and technical science communication.

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:18.200
You might be asking yourself, okay, well, I've got a lot of old R Markdowns that I want

00:16:18.200 --> 00:16:19.200
to use.

00:16:19.200 --> 00:16:22.400
So for some of you, keep using them, we're still going to maintain R Markdown, you don't

00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:25.880
have to switch if you don't want to, you can keep using it.

00:16:25.880 --> 00:16:30.640
But Cordo can actually render R Markdown documents, so you can take your existing R Markdown documents

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:34.640
and render them over to whatever format you want via Cordo.

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:38.099
So whether you're staying in R Markdown or switching them over, you can still render

00:16:38.099 --> 00:16:39.099
them out.

00:16:39.099 --> 00:16:44.200
And in fact, this unification of different formats, let's say we were trying to render

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:45.200
to HTML and to PDF.

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:50.559
For HTML, we use things like CSS and raw HTML, for PDF, we're going to be using LaTeX and

00:16:50.559 --> 00:16:52.559
other things like that.

00:16:52.559 --> 00:16:56.359
Normally you'd have to write a lot of manual code in there to convert between them.

00:16:56.359 --> 00:17:00.960
But for this document, I'm not writing any CSS or any LaTeX, I'm only using Cordo, and

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:03.840
I can create a nicely typeset document like this.

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:07.119
It's got a picture in the sidebar, it's got a table of contents and all sorts of other

00:17:07.119 --> 00:17:09.079
footnotes and things.

00:17:09.079 --> 00:17:11.680
That document in PDF looks almost identical.

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:15.319
You're obviously constrained to what PDF can do, so you don't have hover text and you don't

00:17:15.319 --> 00:17:20.520
have the same type of interactivity as HTML, but without having to write anything else

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:25.560
besides Cordo code or Cordo Markdown, I'm able to generate these two very well typeset

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:30.760
documents from a single source, so single source publishing for this.

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:34.199
And again, Cordo is extended for other languages, so this typesetting and all the different

00:17:34.199 --> 00:17:40.160
things it brings are made with Lua filters rather than an R package, so things that people

00:17:40.199 --> 00:17:46.319
write in Python language and in R or in Julia are cross-language and cross-format compatible.

00:17:46.319 --> 00:17:49.920
So we're meeting these users in their native language, so when you are collaborating, you're

00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:55.560
not fighting with each other, but you're merging around a common syntax.

00:17:55.560 --> 00:17:58.760
Those people might ask, well, what to do about my existing IPython notebooks?

00:17:58.760 --> 00:18:00.640
I don't want to get rid of them.

00:18:00.640 --> 00:18:01.880
The answer is essentially the same.

00:18:01.880 --> 00:18:06.079
I can Cordo render any IPython notebook and send it over to the format.

00:18:06.079 --> 00:18:10.000
The only difference is an IPython notebook might actually store computation inside of

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.280
it, so you can either tell Cordo, hey, take this document and render it top to bottom

00:18:14.280 --> 00:18:21.000
or using the embedded execution, just format it out to something else or change the format

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.439
to the final output.

00:18:23.439 --> 00:18:29.520
And in fact, Cordo has a helper tool to allow you to convert between a plain text QMD and

00:18:29.520 --> 00:18:34.119
an IPython notebook itself, so you can swap back and forth whether using IPython notebooks

00:18:34.119 --> 00:18:36.880
or Cordo without having to change the source code.

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:40.719
You can actually convert back and forth between them.

00:18:40.719 --> 00:18:44.579
You can also extend Cordo, so we have things like short code, so if you wanted to add something

00:18:44.579 --> 00:18:48.359
into the open source Cordo, you could use a short code like this that will insert things

00:18:48.359 --> 00:18:53.660
like fun awesome icons, or you can add filters that will actually change the overall appearance

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:57.520
of a document, and again, this is not limited to any language, so any extensions that you

00:18:57.520 --> 00:19:02.040
write in a Python world work in R and anything in R works in Python.

00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:05.719
You can also add entirely new formats, so maybe you want to create a format for your

00:19:05.719 --> 00:19:06.719
company.

00:19:06.719 --> 00:19:10.239
You can create your own cool company format for Reveal.js.

00:19:10.239 --> 00:19:14.560
So these extensions allow you to go further with Cordo as we move forward and add more

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:15.560
things.

00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:20.520
And then lastly, I mentioned this idea of Cordo pubs, so Cordo can actually publish

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:24.920
the thing you just rendered to the Internet, so you can publish to GitHub or to Netlify

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:29.020
or connect, but we're now announcing that Cordo pubs exist.

00:19:29.020 --> 00:19:32.939
It's a free resource that allows you to publish anything you create locally and put that out

00:19:32.939 --> 00:19:36.579
on the web at a URL you choose and manage all of your documents that you're publishing

00:19:36.579 --> 00:19:38.260
out.

00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:39.260
So this is very exciting.

00:19:39.260 --> 00:19:42.979
I would recommend signing up quickly to go grab your preferred user name, and you can

00:19:42.979 --> 00:19:45.140
use that.

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:49.180
The last part I'll say is, again, you can use Cordo in RStudio Connect and RStudio Workbench

00:19:49.180 --> 00:19:53.060
already, so if you do have those products available for you, we have some examples of

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:57.300
using them, and you're welcome to go check them out, and with that, we're getting close

00:19:57.300 --> 00:20:01.739
to the end of the talk, so I want to give a shout-out to the entire Cordo dev team.

00:20:01.739 --> 00:20:06.500
Cordo is crafted with love and care by the same team that works on Cordo in R Markdown,

00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:10.500
and you can contribute yourself if you want to contribute, whether an extension or to

00:20:10.500 --> 00:20:13.339
the Cordo CLI itself.

00:20:13.339 --> 00:20:17.500
I've got a summary of the talks that are available and other things coming up, and some takeaways

00:20:17.500 --> 00:20:21.619
with the batteries included, the shared syntax, the ability to choose your editor and your

00:20:21.619 --> 00:20:25.579
language, and the fact that R Markdown is not going anywhere, we're still maintaining

00:20:25.579 --> 00:20:29.540
it, but we're going to be building in a lot of our new features into Cordo.

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:31.020
With that, thank you for your time.

00:20:31.020 --> 00:20:34.099
I'm happy to take questions after the fact down in the lounge, or you can reach out to

00:20:34.099 --> 00:20:35.099
me on Twitter.

00:20:35.099 --> 00:20:37.099
Thank you, and have a great and safe conference.

